<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_number` row that
    creates the auto-numbering counter for the `x_casemgmt_case_task` custom
    table inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    This counter is what produces the human-readable, sequential identifiers
    (TASK0000001, TASK0000002, ...) for every row inserted into the
    x_casemgmt_case_task table - whether the row is created by an authorized
    internal user via the native ServiceNow form, by the seed-data Update Set
    block, by the case state-machine flows, or by the seed_demo_data.js
    server-side script. It is the parallel sibling of
    ./sys_number_x_casemgmt_case.xml (which produces CASE0000001) and is
    structurally identical except for the prefix, table, sys_id, category,
    and sys_update_name fields.

    Per AAP Section 0.4.1 (target directory layout) and AAP Section 0.5.1
    (File-by-File Transformation Plan):
        servicenow-case-management-poc/numbers/sys_number_x_casemgmt_case_task.xml
            CREATE | (no source counterpart) | "Number prefix TASK, padding 7"

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim), x_casemgmt_case_task
    does NOT enumerate a `number` field as one of its 6 user-prompt-required
    fields (case, subject, type, status, assigned_to, due_date). However,
    every ServiceNow sys_db_object record provisions an auto-number column
    by default via its <number_ref> linkage; the parent table record at
    ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_task.xml explicitly declares
        <number_ref display_value="TASK" source="x_casemgmt">
            x_casemgmt_case_task_number
        </number_ref>
    which means the table row REQUIRES this sys_number record to exist for
    its number_ref to resolve cleanly during Update Set preview.

    The auto-numbered TASK0000001 identifier supports:
      (a) human-readable identification of demo tasks in
          ../seed-data/tasks/x_casemgmt_case_task_demo_*.xml so the AAP's
          "at least one open and one closed task per demo case" verification
          can be done by browsing task numbers like TASK0000001 - critical
          for visual validation of AAP Section 0.7.4's minimum demo-data
          thresholds.
      (b) the validate_resolved_transition subflow (AAP Section 0.5.5) which
          surfaces the literal blocking-error message "All tasks must be
          closed before resolving this case." - the agent reading that
          error needs to be able to identify the offending task(s) by
          their number.
      (c) the ../reports/x_casemgmt_my_overdue_tasks.xml report which lists
          tasks where due_date < Today AND status != Closed - operators
          read the task numbers off this list to navigate to specific tasks.
      (d) any future integration that benefits from stable, sequential,
          human-friendly identifiers.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-task-plugin/src/main/java/
      com/armedia/acm/plugins/task/model/AcmTask.java
        Line 65: `private Long taskId;`
        Lines 172-178: getter / setter for taskId
        Line 396: hashCode() participation
      The source-side primary key is a simple Hibernate-generated Long
      (taskId), assigned sequentially by JPA based on the Hibernate
      sequence/identity strategy at insert time. The target consolidates
      both the platform-internal primary key (sys_id - a 32-char UUID
      assigned automatically by ServiceNow) AND the human-readable
      external identifier (TASK0000001) into ServiceNow's native two-
      column model: sys_id is the immutable UUID; the auto-number column
      driven by THIS record is the user-facing identifier. Unlike the
      ArkCase Long taskId, ServiceNow's TASK0000001 format is
      user-readable, prefixed for disambiguation across tables (CASE vs
      TASK vs PARTY), zero-padded for sortable display, and persistent
      across record renumbering events.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: this record's <sys_scope> and
        <sys_package> bind it to the scoped application
        `x_casemgmt`. The <table> element points at the
        SCOPED case_task table `x_casemgmt_case_task` - NOT at the OOB
        `task`, `incident`, or any other global table. Per AAP Section
        0.3.2 verbatim: "no edits to ... `task`, `incident`, or any
        out-of-the-box ServiceNow tables." Writing <table>task</table>
        here would associate this counter with the global `task` table
        (a global-scope write that would violate AAP). NO global-scope
        writes occur in this record.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: every cross-reference
        (<sys_scope>, <sys_package>, <table>) resolves by NAME (the
        scope source name `x_casemgmt` and the table
        name `x_casemgmt_case_task`), not by literal sys_id. The
        <sys_id> text-node value is THIS record's own deterministic
        primary key (MD5 of the canonical record name
        `sys_number_x_casemgmt_case_task` =
        ee298f5e8c95d67c6fa9a97f5b390782) and is NOT a reference to
        any other record. Per AAP Section 0.7.2: "the `sys_id` of THIS
        record is the record's own primary key - not a reference field".
      - The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention;
        ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the
        scope id must be concrete in the XML before export. Do NOT substitute it with a real scope id.
      - <prefix>TASK</prefix> is uppercase, exactly 4 characters, NOT
        `Task`, NOT `task`, NOT `TSK`. Per AAP Section 0.5.1 verbatim
        ("Number prefix TASK, padding 7"), TASK is the prefix component
        of the required TASK0000001 format. The platform's default
        auto-number padding is 7 digits when the prefix is short and
        the initial maximum is 0, so the first generated identifier is
        TASK0000001 - matching ServiceNow's standard convention for
        similar OOB tables (INC0000001, CHG0000001, PRB0000001,
        SCTASK0000001) and parallel to the case sibling's CASE0000001
        format.
      - <maximum>0</maximum> and <number>0</number>: both starting at 0.
        After the platform processes the first GlideRecord.insert() of
        an x_casemgmt_case_task row, the counter increments to 1 and
        renders as TASK0000001. Successive inserts produce TASK0000002,
        TASK0000003, etc. The counter persists across server restarts
        because it lives in the sys_number table (not in volatile
        memory).
      - <category>x_casemgmt_case_task</category>: ServiceNow's convention
        for the `category` column on sys_number is to set it to the
        target table name (mirroring the <table> field). This is purely
        an organizational grouping; the platform does not derive runtime
        behavior from it.
      - No PII: the counter stores only synthetic auto-generated
        identifiers (TASK0000001, etc.); no real names, email addresses,
        or organizational identifiers are derived from or stored here.
      - Re-exportability: the deterministic <sys_id> (MD5-derived
        32-char lowercase hex `ee298f5e8c95d67c6fa9a97f5b390782`)
        ensures that re-exporting the Update Set produces the same
        sys_id every time, preventing "duplicate-record" errors during
        fresh-PDI re-import preview (AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7).
      - MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE (AAP Section 0.7.2): this record contains
        ONLY the elements enumerated in the agent prompt - <category>,
        <prefix>, <maximum>, <number>, <table>, <sys_scope>,
        <sys_package>, <sys_policy/>, <sys_id>, <sys_mod_count>,
        <sys_created_by>, <sys_created_on>, <sys_updated_by>,
        <sys_updated_on>, <sys_class_name>, <sys_update_name>. No
        additional fields are added beyond what is required.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      This record MUST load AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - must exist
          before any scoped record can resolve <sys_scope>)
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (application
          record - <sys_package> resolves by source name to this)
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_task.xml (target table - <table>
          element references it by name)
      This record MUST load BEFORE consumers that read or write the
      auto-generated task identifier:
        - The number_ref resolution check during Update Set preview for
          ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_task.xml (the parent table's
          <number_ref> binding is checked at preview time and requires
          this sys_number record to be present in the Update Set).
        - All ../seed-data/tasks/x_casemgmt_case_task_demo_*.xml
          records (demo task rows would receive auto-numbers from this
          counter when inserted; the seed records themselves may also
          carry pre-populated TASK0000XXX values that depend on this
          counter being aligned).
        - ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js (idempotent server-side seed
          script that uses GlideRecord lookups by task `number`).
        - ../reports/x_casemgmt_my_overdue_tasks.xml (the overdue tasks
          report displays the task `number` column produced by this
          counter).
        - ../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml (the
          subflow that enforces "All tasks must be closed before
          resolving this case." - when blocking, the task number from
          this counter is shown in the error context).
        - ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
          (queries x_casemgmt_case_task and references task numbers
          generated by this counter).

    Validation gate impact (AAP Section 0.7.3):
      - Gate 1 (Data model): "All 3 custom tables created with correct
        fields and types - Zero missing mandatory fields." This record
        contributes by providing the auto-number machinery for the
        x_casemgmt_case_task table; the gate passes when the parent
        table's <number_ref> resolves cleanly during Update Set preview.
      - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Update Set loads without errors on a
        fresh PDI instance." This record's deterministic sys_id makes
        re-exports stable and idempotent on re-import.
-->
<record_update table="sys_number">
    <sys_number action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <category>x_casemgmt_case_task</category>
        <maximum>0</maximum>
        <number>0</number>
        <number_of_digits>7</number_of_digits>
        <prefix>TASK</prefix>
        <sys_class_name>sys_number</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>ee298f5e8c95d67c6fa9a97f5b390782</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_number_x_casemgmt_case_task</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <table>x_casemgmt_case_task</table>
    </sys_number>
</record_update>
